Behavior contract (per H.4 spec):
  ✓ scanned < POLL_BATCH_SIZE: no self-invoke (most common case)
  ✓ scanned === POLL_BATCH_SIZE && chainDepth < POLL_MAX_CHAIN_DEPTH:
    fire InvokeCommand with InvocationType='Event' (async fire-and-
    forget) and chainDepth+1 in payload
  ✓ scanned === POLL_BATCH_SIZE && chainDepth === POLL_MAX_CHAIN_DEPTH:
    refuse + log warn; remaining rows wait for next EB tick
  ✓ Throughput math: chain depth 5 × batch 100 = up to 600 rows per
    EB tick. 1 EB tick/min → up to 600 rows/min. Per-workspace cap
    (H.3) means single-workspace throughput is unaffected (still 5
    rows/sweep regardless of chain).
  ✓ Self-invoke uses InvocationType='Event' so the originating
    Lambda doesn't pay the synchronous round-trip cost. The next
    hop's Lambda starts cold-start in ~50-200ms.
  ✓ Lambda InvocationType='Event' failures (IAM not yet attached,
    throttling) are caught + logged non-fatal — the originating
    sweep's results are preserved. Next EB tick picks up the
    remaining rows (visible after H.1 lease expires in 5 min).
  ✓ Self-invoke race vs lease: a hop landing on the SAME pool of
    rows sees them leased → empty SELECT → scanned=0 → no further
    chain. The chain only fans out if there's truly more work.

Test specs (3 new):
  1. "H.4: sweep that scanned < POLL_BATCH_SIZE does NOT
      self-invoke" — POLL_BATCH_SIZE=10, SELECT returns 0 rows,
      asserts lambdaSendMock not called.
  2. "H.4: sweep that scanned === POLL_BATCH_SIZE with chainDepth
      < cap → self-invoke with chainDepth+1" — POLL_BATCH_SIZE=2,
      2 rows for registered fast_kit adapter, asserts lambdaSendMock
      called once with FunctionName='basics-cron-kicker',
      InvocationType='Event', payload={kind, chainDepth:1}.
  3. "H.4: sweep at chainDepth >= POLL_MAX_CHAIN_DEPTH refuses to
      self-invoke (cap enforced)" — POLL_BATCH_SIZE=1, chainDepth=5,
      asserts lambdaSendMock not called.

Test-isolation fix:
  - "two parallel sweeps" used vi.doMock("postgres", smartTag)
    which persisted across vi.resetModules() and leaked into H.4
    tests (smart tag returned empty for non-claim queries, causing
    scanned=0 in the H.4 tests). Fix: restore the default postgres
    mock at end of parallel-sweeps test via
    vi.doMock("postgres", () => ({ default: () => sqlTagFn })).

Adversarial review (review-1.json):
  Opus 4.7 via Agent tool; verdict: ship; 0 blockers; 6 nits.
  Nits: spec text stale (~500/min vs actual 600/min after batch
  bump), H.3 cap rate-limits single-workspace throughput regardless
  of chain, self-invoke-fail creates 4-min reprocess delay (lease-
  bounded; not data loss), reservedConcurrency cap deferred to H.6,
  hoisted lambdaSendMock is fine but future doMock would need
  restoration discipline, Buffer.from vs TextEncoder portability
  nit.

Notes / decisions:
  - InvocationType='Event' over 'RequestResponse': async fire-and-
    forget keeps the originating Lambda's wall-time low (no waiting
    for the next hop's sweep to finish). Lambda guarantees the
    invocation is enqueued + retried internally.
  - 5-hop cap is a per-tick ceiling. If load consistently saturates
    the batch (every EB tick + every chain hop both drain 100 rows),
    we get 600/min sustained = 36,000/hr = 864,000/day. That's
    likely enough for the foreseeable future; H.6 will add metrics
    so we can see saturation patterns before they become a problem.
  - Did NOT thread an AbortSignal to cancel in-flight adapter HTTP
    calls when the Lambda is killed. The H.1 lease (5min) covers
    the "Lambda killed mid-sweep" case via idempotent re-fetch.

